      "content": "I apologize for the previous response; I misunderstood the instruction to \"stick to the technical side\" and inadvertently included a metaphor about a goblin barometer that was neither accurate nor helpful. I will now provide a strictly technical explanation of the pitot tube's physics, the consequences of blockage, and the common causes of blockages, keeping the tone professional and focused on aviation engineering.\n\n**How a Pitot Tube Works**\nA pitot tube operates on Bernoulli's principle, which states that an increase in the speed of a fluid occurs simultaneously with a decrease in static pressure. The tube has two distinct pressure ports: the **total pressure port** (the pitot opening) and the **static pressure port** (holes on the side of the tube).\n\n1.  **Total Pressure (Stagnation Pressure):** As the aircraft moves forward, air strikes the front opening of the pitot tube. This air is brought to a complete stop (stagnation), converting its kinetic energy (velocity) into pressure energy. This is the highest pressure measured.\n2.  **Static Pressure:** The side holes are located in an area where the airflow is parallel to the tube's axis, meaning the air speed relative to the",
