      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No, the results are not the same, and the consequences differ significantly depending on which port is obstructed.\n\nIf the **main pitot tube** (the forward-facing opening) gets clogged, the aircraft loses its ability to measure total pressure. The airspeed indicator will read **zero** (or a very low value) regardless of how fast the plane is moving, because the sensor is no longer feeling the dynamic pressure of the oncoming air. This is a critical \"false zero\" situation that can lead to a stall if the pilot doesn't realize they are flying at high speed.\n\nIf the **side static ports** get clogged, the aircraft loses its reference for ambient air pressure. The airspeed indicator will read **higher than the actual speed** (a false high indication). This happens because the instrument is comparing the correct total pressure against a pressure that is artificially high (since the clogged port cannot equalize with the outside atmosphere). This can cause the pilot to believe the plane is flying faster than it actually is, potentially leading to an inadvertent stall if the pilot reduces power thinking they are in a high-speed regime.\n\nBoth scenarios are dangerous, but they present opposite errors: one hides the speed entirely, while",
